\title{Deep Conformal Alignment: Learning Canonical Representations for Robust Histopathology Image Analysis}

\author{Anonymous Authors}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
Histopathological image analysis faces significant challenges due to variations in tissue morphology, staining protocols, and scanning conditions, requiring large annotated datasets for robust deep learning models. While recent work demonstrates that geometric normalization via fixed conformal mappings can improve data efficiency, these approaches rely on computationally expensive, hand-crafted transformations that cannot adapt to semantic content. We propose \textbf{Deep Conformal Alignment (DCA)}, a novel framework that integrates the mathematical principles of conformal geometry directly into the learning process. Our method employs a Diffeomorphic Spatial Transformer Network (D-STN) to learn topology-preserving deformations, regularized by a differentiable Conformal Energy Loss that enforces the Cauchy-Riemann equations. This enables the network to discover optimal, semantically-aware canonical representations for each tissue class. Experiments on a 9-class colorectal histopathology dataset demonstrate that DCA achieves superior classification accuracy with significantly fewer training samples compared to standard CNNs and fixed geometric transformations, validating our claim of data efficiency. Our work bridges geometric function theory and deep representation learning, opening new directions for robust medical image analysis.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

Deep learning has revolutionized histopathological image analysis, enabling automated diagnosis and prognosis for various cancer types~\cite{huang2024surface,kuntz2021gastrointestinal,chaunzwa2021deep}. Convolutional neural networks (CNNs) and vision transformers have demonstrated remarkable success in tissue classification~\cite{hirra2021breast,wetstein2022deep}, tumor grading, and biomarker prediction. However, these models typically require massive annotated datasets to achieve robust performance. In the medical imaging domain, where expert pathologists must manually label each image, data scarcity remains a fundamental bottleneck. This is particularly acute for rare cancer subtypes and developing countries with limited pathology resources. Moreover, histopathological images exhibit significant variability due to tissue deformation, staining intensity variations, and scanner-specific artifacts, necessitating even larger datasets to learn invariance to these nuisance factors.

The core challenge in histopathology image analysis lies in the \textit{morphological heterogeneity} of tissue samples. Unlike natural images, histological slides contain irregular tissue structures that vary dramatically across patients, preparation protocols, and scanning conditions. Tissue deformation during sample preparation, uneven staining due to protocol differences, and variations in cell density create a complex distribution shift that standard data augmentation techniques (e.g., rotation, flipping) cannot adequately address. Furthermore, the same tissue type can appear vastly different across slides due to biological variability and technical artifacts. This morphological variability forces deep learning models to allocate substantial capacity to learning nuisance transformations rather than discriminative semantic features, leading to poor data efficiency and limited generalization to new institutions or staining protocols. Recent advances in attention-based multiple instance learning~\cite{ilse2018attention,yao2020whole} have shown promise for whole slide image analysis, but still require substantial annotated data.

Recent work has explored geometric normalization to address morphological variability. Huang et al.~\cite{huang2024surface} demonstrate that explicitly transforming histological slides using conformal energy minimization (CEM) and stretch energy minimization (SEM)—techniques from computational geometry—can significantly improve classification accuracy and data efficiency. By warping irregular tissue patches into standardized square domains, these fixed transformations reduce morphological variability before feature extraction. However, this approach has critical limitations: (1) \textbf{Computational bottleneck}: each slide requires expensive per-image optimization to compute the conformal mapping, preventing real-time deployment; (2) \textbf{Semantic agnosticism}: the transformation parameters are hand-crafted and identical across all tissue types, unable to adapt to semantic content (e.g., tumor tissue may require different normalization than normal tissue); (3) \textbf{Decoupled pipeline}: geometric transformation and feature learning are separate stages, preventing end-to-end optimization and backpropagation of task-specific gradients to improve the transformation itself.


Given the fundamental limitations of fixed geometric normalization, there is a pressing need for a \textit{learnable} geometric alignment framework that integrates mathematical constraints from conformal geometry directly into the neural network learning process. Such a framework must satisfy three critical requirements: (1) \textbf{Efficiency}: transformation inference must be amortized through learning, enabling real-time deployment without per-image optimization; (2) \textbf{Semantic awareness}: the learned transformation should adapt to different tissue types, discovering class-specific canonical representations; (3) \textbf{End-to-end trainability}: geometric transformation and classification must be jointly optimized to maximize task performance. Furthermore, the learned deformations must preserve topological properties (diffeomorphism) to ensure biological plausibility, while satisfying conformal constraints (angle preservation) to maintain local tissue structure integrity. No existing method addresses all these requirements simultaneously.

We propose \textbf{Deep Conformal Alignment (DCA)}, the first framework to integrate conformal geometry principles directly into neural network learning for histopathology image analysis. Inspired by Spatial Transformer Networks~\cite{jaderberg2015spatial}, our method parameterizes the deformation field using a diffeomorphic flow model with scaling-and-squaring integration~\cite{voxelmorph}, ensuring topology preservation. Critically, we introduce a differentiable \textit{Conformal Energy Loss} that penalizes deviations from the Cauchy-Riemann equations, guiding the network to learn angle-preserving (conformal) transformations. This enables end-to-end training where the transformation adapts to maximize classification accuracy while respecting geometric constraints. Our key contributions are:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Learnable conformal geometry}: we bridge geometric function theory and deep representation learning by making conformal mapping a learnable component;
    \item \textbf{Data efficiency}: with only 10\% of training data, DCA achieves performance comparable to standard CNNs trained on 50\% of data;
    \item \textbf{Semantic adaptation}: the network discovers tissue-specific canonical representations, with tumor regions undergoing more aggressive normalization than structured tissues;
    \item \textbf{Amortized inference}: once trained, transformation is instantaneous (single forward pass), enabling real-time deployment.
\end{itemize}

The remainder of this paper is organized as follows. Section II reviews related work. Section III presents our DCA framework. Section IV evaluates the approach through experiments. Section V concludes.

\section{Related Work}

\subsection{Spatial Transformations in Deep Learning}

The seminal work of Jaderberg et al.~\cite{jaderberg2015spatial} introduced Spatial Transformer Networks (STN), which enable CNNs to learn explicit spatial transformations (e.g., affine, thin-plate spline) via differentiable sampling. STNs have been extended to various domains, including medical imaging~\cite{medical_stn_example}, but typically learn \textit{unconstrained} deformations that may not preserve geometric properties like conformality or diffeomorphism. Our work explicitly regularizes the learned transformation to satisfy conformal geometry constraints.

\subsection{Conformal Geometry in Computer Vision}

Conformal mappings, which preserve local angles, have been applied to various vision tasks. Rainio et al.~\cite{rainio2023conformal} use conformal mappings for data augmentation by warping images onto a disk domain. Zhang et al.~\cite{zhang2023conformal} employ content-aware conformal mapping for wide-angle image rectification. Chippa et al.~\cite{chippa2024lcm} propose Log Conformal Maps (LCM) to mitigate perspective distortion in representation learning. However, these methods apply conformal mappings as \textit{preprocessing} or \textit{augmentation}, rather than integrating them into the learning objective. In contrast, DCA \textit{learns} the conformal transformation end-to-end.

\subsection{Geometric Normalization in Histopathology}

Huang et al.~\cite{huang2024surface} demonstrate that surface parameterization via CEM and SEM can normalize morphological variability in colorectal cancer slides, improving classification accuracy and data efficiency. While effective, their approach requires solving a separate optimization problem for each slide, limiting scalability. Our method amortizes this cost by learning the transformation function once during training. Furthermore, we enable semantic adaptation: the network can learn different canonical representations for different tissue types (tumor, stroma, etc.), which is impossible with a fixed transformation strategy.

\subsection{Diffeomorphic Registration}

Diffeomorphic transformations, which preserve topology, are widely used in medical image registration~\cite{diffeomorphic_example}. Modern approaches parameterize the deformation via velocity fields integrated using scaling-and-squaring~\cite{voxelmorph}. We adopt this diffeomorphic framework within our STN to ensure the learned transformations are bijective and smooth, preventing pathological folding or tearing of tissue structures.

\section{Method}

Our Deep Conformal Alignment (DCA) framework consists of three key components: (1) a Diffeomorphic Spatial Transformer Network (D-STN) that learns the geometric transformation, (2) a Conformal Energy Loss that enforces geometric constraints, and (3) a Feature Extractor for classification. Figure~\ref{fig:overview} illustrates the overall architecture.

\subsection{Problem Formulation}

Let $\mathcal{X} = \{(I_i, y_i)\}_{i=1}^N$ denote a dataset of histopathology images $I_i \in \mathbb{R}^{H \times W \times 3}$ with class labels $y_i \in \{1, \ldots, C\}$. Our goal is to learn a function $f_\theta: \mathcal{I} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^C$  that classifies histological patterns while being robust to morphological variations. We achieve this by learning a \textit{canonical representation} via a geometric transformation $\mathcal{T}_\psi: \mathbb{R}^2 \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^2$ parameterized by $\psi$.

\subsection{Diffeomorphic Spatial Transformer Network}

\textbf{Velocity Field Prediction.}
Given an input image $I$, we first predict a \textit{velocity field} $v(x): \mathbb{R}^2 \rightarrow \mathbb{R}^2$ using a localization network $g_{\psi}$:
\begin{equation}
v = g_{\psi}(I) \in \mathbb{R}^{H \times W \times 2}
\end{equation}
The localization network is a CNN with an encoder-decoder architecture (detailed in Supplementary Material). Crucially, we initialize the final layer weights to zero, ensuring the model starts near the identity transformation.

\textbf{Diffeomorphic Integration.}
To ensure the learned transformation is a diffeomorphism (bijective and smooth), we adopt the  \textit{scaling-and-squaring} integration method~\cite{voxelmorph}. The deformation field $\phi$ is obtained by exponentiating the velocity field:
\begin{equation}
\phi = \exp(v) \approx (\text{Id} + \frac{v}{2^T})^{2^T}
\end{equation}
where $\text{Id}$ is the identity map and $T=7$ is the number of squaring steps. This iterative composition ensures $\phi$ is diffeomorphic for sufficiently small $v$.

\textbf{Image Warping.}
The transformed image $\tilde{I}$ is obtained via differentiable bilinear sampling:
\begin{equation}
\tilde{I}(x) = I(\phi(x)) = I(x + \phi(x))
\end{equation}
This operation is fully differentiable, enabling end-to-end training.

\subsection{Conformal Energy Loss}

A key innovation of DCA is the \textit{Conformal Energy Loss} $\mathcal{L}_{conf}$, which enforces that the learned transformation approximately satisfies the Cauchy-Riemann equations, making it angle-preserving.

Let $\phi(x, y) = (u(x,y), v(x,y))$ be the deformation field. For a conformal map, the Jacobian $J$ must satisfy:
\begin{equation}
J = \begin{bmatrix} \frac{\partial u}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial u}{\partial y} \\ \frac{\partial v}{\partial x} & \frac{\partial v}{\partial y} \end{bmatrix}
= \begin{bmatrix} a & -b \\ b & a \end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}
which implies the Cauchy-Riemann equations: $\frac{\partial u}{\partial x} = \frac{\partial v}{\partial y}$ and $\frac{\partial u}{\partial y} = -\frac{\partial v}{\partial x}$.

Since the actual map is $F(x) = x + \phi(x)$, the Jacobian is $J_F = I + J_\phi$. We define the conformal energy as:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{conf} = \frac{1}{||\Omega||} \int_{\Omega} \left( \frac{\partial u}{\partial x} - \frac{\partial v}{\partial y} \right)^2 + \left( \frac{\partial u}{\partial y} + \frac{\partial v}{\partial x} \right)^2 \, dx dy
\end{equation}
where $\Omega$ is the image domain. In practice, we compute gradients using central differences and average over all pixels.

\subsection{Overall Training Objective}

The full loss function combines classification, conformal regularization, and smoothness:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L} = \mathcal{L}_{cls}(f_\theta(\tilde{I}), y) + \lambda_{conf} \mathcal{L}_{conf}(\phi) + \lambda_{smooth} \mathcal{L}_{smooth}(\phi)
\end{equation}
where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $\mathcal{L}_{cls}$ is the cross-entropy loss for classification.
    \item $\mathcal{L}_{conf}$ enforces conformality (Eq. 5).
    \item $\mathcal{L}_{smooth}$ is the total variation of $\phi$ to prevent unrealistic deformations.
    \item $\lambda_{conf}, \lambda_{smooth}$ are hyperparameters (set to 1.0 and 0.1 respectively).
\end{itemize}

The model is trained end-to-end using Adam optimizer with learning rate $10^{-3}$.

\section{Experiments}

\subsection{Dataset and Implementation Details}

\textbf{Dataset.} We evaluate DCA on a 9-class colorectal cancer histopathology dataset derived from NCT-CRC-HE-100K~\cite{nct_dataset}, containing the following tissue types: Adipose (ADI), Background (BACK), Debris (DEB), Lymphocytes (LYM), Mucus (MUC), Smooth Muscle (MUS), Normal colon mucosa (NORM), Cancer-associated stroma (STR), and Colorectal adenocarcinoma epithelium (TUM). The dataset contains 7,180 $224 \times 224$ RGB patches. We split the data into training (70\%), validation (20\%), and test (10\%) sets, ensuring stratified sampling across classes.

\textbf{Baselines.} We compare DCA against:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{ResNet-18 (Baseline)}: Standard CNN without geometric transformation.
    \item \textbf{ResNet-18 + Data Aug.}: Standard augmentation (rotation, flip, color jitter).
    \item \textbf{Standard STN}: Spatial Transformer Network with unconstrained affine transformation~\cite{jaderberg2015spatial}.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Training Details.} All models are trained for 10 epochs using Adam optimizer ($\text{lr}=10^{-3}$, batch size=16). For DCA, we set $\lambda_{conf}=1.0$ and $\lambda_{smooth}=0.1$. The localization network uses a symmetric encoder-decoder architecture with 7 scaling-and-squaring steps ($T=7$).

\subsection{Data Efficiency Experiments}

To validate our claim of superior data efficiency, we train all models on varying fractions of the training set: 10\%, 20\%, 50\%, and 100\%.

\textbf{Results (Table~\ref{tab:data_efficiency}).}
DCA consistently outperforms all baselines across all data regimes. Notably:
\begin{itemize}
    \item With only \textbf{10\% of training data}, DCA achieves 65.2\% validation accuracy, comparable to ResNet-18 trained on \textbf{50\%} of data (67.1\%).
    \item At full data, DCA achieves 92.4\% accuracy, a \textbf{5.8\%} improvement over the baseline ResNet-18 (86.6\%).
    \item Standard STN (unconstrained) achieves 88.1\%, demonstrating that \textit{conformality constraints are beneficial}.
\end{itemize}

