\subsection{Visualization of Learned Transformations}

Figure~\ref{fig:visualizations} shows that DCA learns semantically meaningful transformations: tumor regions (TUM) undergo more aggressive normalization to remove irregular boundaries, while structured tissues (MUS, NORM) show subtle alignment. The conformal constraint ensures local angles are preserved, preventing unrealistic distortions.

\subsection{Ablation Study}

We ablate key components of DCA:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{w/o Conformal Loss ($\lambda_{conf}=0$)}: Accuracy drops to 88.9\%, showing the importance of geometric constraints.
    \item \textbf{w/o Diffeomorphic Integration (direct $\phi$ prediction)}: Accuracy drops to 87.2\%, indicating topology preservation is beneficial.
\end{itemize}

\section{Conclusion}

We presented Deep Conformal Alignment (DCA), the first framework to integrate conformal geometry principles directly into neural network learning for histopathology image analysis. By combining a Diffeomorphic Spatial Transformer Network with a differentiable Conformal Energy Loss, DCA learns semantically-aware canonical representations that improve data efficiency and robustness. Experiments on colorectal cancer histopathology demonstrate that DCA achieves strong performance with significantly fewer training samples compared to standard CNNs. Future work will explore extension to whole-slide image analysis and other medical imaging domains.

